This is a student group at the University of Arkansas (Fayetteville) open to undergraduate and graduate students. We are associated with the Center for Inquiry On Campus and the Secular Student Alliance.
Our mission is to provide and maintain systems that facilitate the growth and development of a safe and supportive community for those who leave or are considering leaving the Mormon Church.

This group consists of a variety of different families with secular lifestyles -- some may consider themselves atheists, some agnostics, some secular humanists or naturalists, and many may consider themselves spiritual, but the common thread is that we all are raising our children without organized religion and want them to determine their own beliefs without teaching them any one belief system or dogma.

Oklahoma Atheists (AOK) mission is to develop a community of individuals and families who value and promote critical thinking, freethought, reason and a scientific worldview -- as opposed to the acceptance of faith and dogma -- and who seek to have a positive effect on the community at large through fellowship, ethical and rational discussion, community service, and education. Spanning a wide range (from educational to social), our activities include: dinner meetups, potlucks, family outings, debates, speeches, book clubs, volunteer opportunities, and political events and protests. We welcome all who share the ideals of critical thinking and who reject religious dogma. In addition to cultivating a community, we wish to contribute to and put a face with all the positive things non-believers and people with a secular viewpoint are doing in the world.

The Oklahoma State Secular Organization has two functions. First, it exists as a social gathering point for people who enjoy a secular/naturalistic humanistic lifestyle including but not limited to atheists, agnostics, freethinkers, religious individuals who place strong value on reason and science, etc. Secondly, OSSO’s purpose is to promote a reason based lifestyle by advocating a scientific outlook and critical thinking.
This group was started to get Atheists, Agnostics, Humanists, and other freethinkers a place to chat and meet.
The Omaha Atheists and Agnostic Parenting Group is dedicated to providing area Atheist and Agnostic parents with secular, family focused activities.

Omaha Atheists is a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to building a positive community for non-theists, fostering secular viewpoints, supporting charitable contributions to society, and protecting the separation of church and state.
Did you know that there are atheists everywhere?!?! You may not know it, but we are!

Open on Sundays Social Club is for men and women who just don\'t fit the Utah mold. While everyone else in Utah is at church on Sundays, we meet up and support local businesses who dare to remain open on the "holy sabbath"!
Or Adam, Congregation for Humanistic Judaism

The name Or Adam, Hebrew for "light of humanity," reflects our desire to share our love and respect for Jewish culture and tradition with others and emphasizes that our destiny is not guided by a supernatural force, but by the human power within ourselves. For 25 years, we have been the leading voice for Secular Humanistic Judaism in the Phoenix metropolitan area where we have been providing a community experience that rewards Jewish identity and enriches the dignity of all humankind.
Or Emet, Minnesota Congregation for Humanistic Judaism
We embrace a human-centered philosophy and that combines rational thinking and scientific inquiry with the celebration of Jewish culture and identity.
Orange County Congregation for Secular Humanistic Jews

Humanistic Judaism embraces a human-centered philosophy that combines rational thinking with a celebration of Jewish culture and identity. It affirms the power and responsibility of human beings to shape their own lives independent of supernatural authority.

Founded in 1969 as the Secular Jewish Association by a group of families, Oraynu is based on the cultural and philosophical ideals of the Jewish Enlightenment (Haskalah) that originated more than 200 years ago. It has since been active in the establishment and development of both the North American and International movements for Secular Humanistic Judaism.
O4SR is a nonprofit corporation formed to promote science and reason. We seek to develop rational thought and action through the application of scientific methods and critical thinking.
Founded in December 2002, Orlando Freethinkers & Humanists is the oldest and most active freethinking humanist group in the Orlando area.

This is a social club for freethinkers, with NO fees to join. Parents & kids of all ages are welcome! We are based in Celebration, but welcome people from anywhere in central Florida. The goal of this group is socialization, not activism: getting together at restaurants, parks, house parties, theme parks, and whatever else you can think of.

The goal of this group is to meet and discuss short texts such as magazine articles, articles from academic journals, and book chapters. The idea is to take the best parts of a book club--having a group of people who have read the same text--and combine it with a small group discussion, a la what one would find in a seminar course (without the fear of grades!). Thus, with shorter articles and chapters, we can spend more time engaged in talking about our thoughts, insights, questions, and connections with the subject.

Our goals are to:- Establish a home for atheists, agnostics, and other freethinkers at the University of Wisconsin - Oshkosh.- Engage believers in gods, psychics, and all other supernatural occurrences in productive and friendly discussion.- Continuously educate ourselves with regard to new scientific discoveries as well as established fields such as evolution.- Continuously educate ourselves with regard to the beliefs of our opponents so that we may truly understand their arguments and speak from a position of knowledge.- Present a positive view of atheism to the community.- Establish relationships with other related organizations around the world to share ideas.- Offer debates, guest speakers, movie showings, open discussion, and social gatherings for the University of Wisconsin - Oshkosh students and the surrounding community.- Keep an open mind!

The Ottawa Skeptics aim to promote the use of the scientific method, critical thinking and rational thought in our community. Ottawa Skeptics supports high standards of scientific integrity, academic freedom and the free exchange of ideas. We have one bias: Science is the best method for determining objective truth.
This group exists to provide community, networking, outreach, and a social outlet for those who identify themselves as freethinkers. All self-identifying freethinkers are welcome.
Oxford Humanists and Freethinkers Association (Oxford Humanists & Freethinkers)

We explore and discuss Skepticiam, Humanisn, Agnosticism, Pantheism, and other alternatives to mainstream belief systems. Our group will focus on treating people with respect and understanding based on the concept that such behavior is based in ethics and not on religious imperatives. People who think that they may be Humanists or who wish to learn about the Humanistic lifestance are welcome. This is not a proseltyzing group; ours is an open door for seekers.

Pennsylvania Nonbelievers Inc. is a 501(c)3 non-profit educational organization devoted to delivering information for rational and critical thinking. We welcome atheists, agnostics, unbelievers, secularists, humanists and those whose lives are guided by a human-centered morality, not dogma, to come join our lively discussions.
Pacific Lutheran University Secular Student Alliance (PLUSSA)
This is a group for secular students at PLU to discuss and come together as a group.
Meet other local atheists, freethinkers and agnostics. Gather to discuss beliefs and philosophies, and make new friends.

We are a group of parents who are raising our children without religious dogma in the Triangle area. Our group provides a supportive and encouraging community for a wide spectrum of agnostics and atheists where the decision to raise your children without religious dogma is respected. The meetups are kid-friendly and also provide a welcoming social atmosphere for both moms and dads. Expecting parents and those with grown children are also welcome. We have once monthly Sunday morning meetups along with other fun events for kids and adults. Our group members participate in a variety of online discussions concerning topics related to non-religious parenting along with other topics of interest to our members.

Parenting Beyond Religion We are a group of free-thinking families looking to build a community free from religion and supernaturalism. We welcome all labels of free-thought -- Atheists, Agnostics, Humanists, Skeptics, Brights, etc. -- who share the common goal of teaching our children to embrace the scientific world view as a way of understanding the universe.
A group of people to get together and discuss what goes on in the world and how to change that for the better.
The Parkview High School chapter of the Secular Student Alliance.

Peachtree City Humanists was founded to serve a community of agnostic and non-theistic individuals who wish to participate in social and educational activities such as dinners, lunches, coffees, outdoor recreation, discussion groups, and book clubs. Topics that are a focus in our group broadly include science, psychology, philosophy, and include discussions and social activities that attempt to provide social support to our members. This group is democratically governed by a Leadership Team of six individuals. PTCH will not promote any particular political agenda nor will it engage in activism. Maintaining the privacy of our group is of paramount importance.
A group about examining topics with a critical eye.

The Peoria Secular Humanist Society is dedicated to the promotion of the philosophy that a belief in a of supernatural deity is not necessary to live a moral and fulfilling life. We hope to serve as an outreach and form of social support to members of the community who do not follow subscribe to a traditional religion.
Peretz School for Secular Jewish Culture

We provide a quality alternative approach to Jewish life through the appreciation of Jewish history and culture in the context of world history, and the celebration of secular (non-religious) and humanist Jewish traditions.

PhACT encourages people to think critically about their beliefs and about the validity of the information presented to them. PhACT does not presume to tell people what to think but it does give guidance in how to think.

The Philadelphia Atheists Meetup hosts informal monthly discussions on topics related to atheism, such as politics, church-state separation, religions, skepticism, and science. In addition we promote attendance at freethought-related events, such as films and lectures.
Philosophy and Our Lives is a NYC meetup that dwells in the tension between individual life, lived for the first and the last time, and civilization, as a shared creation over generations.
The Phoenix Objectivists is a forum that meets twice a month in the Phoenix metropolitan area and exists to further Objectivism, the moral philosophy of Ayn Rand.
Come enjoy food, drinks, and good ol\' fashioned conversation with others who reject pseudoscience and superstition.

Piedmont Humanists is the original Upstate non-theistic social group for atheists, agnostics, secular humanists and freethinkers. pH exists chiefly to help folks who don\'t fit in with the prevailing religiosity in Upstate South Carolina find a sense of community. We are here to connect, discuss, be active, have fun, pitch in, and otherwise be ourselves -- and hopefully show the other locals that nonbelievers are people, too. Check our events page for meetings and activities!

Pikes Peak Atheist Parents (PPAP) meetups are a way for atheist parents to get together, support each other and find like-minded peers for our children. The majority of our events are in the Pikes Peak region of Colorado, but there are a handful each year in the Denver area, and events may occur state-wide.
This group is designed for skeptics of Pinellas county and elsewhere to get together, enjoy each other\'s company and discuss topics relating to skepticism and critical thinking.

The Pioneer Valley Secularists are a community of non-theists in the Pioneer Valley and surrounding areas. We are committed to promoting the separation of the church and state, secular education, and a positive perception of non-theists among the general public. We hope to contribute to society by providing social, philanthropic, and educational opportunities in an open and welcoming secular environment.

Pittsburgh Secular Freethinkers is a group of freethinkers, including agnostics, atheists, skeptics, deists, and more. We hold regular discussion groups, social events, and service projects, and we seek to provide a meaningful community for the secular residents of Pittsburgh. Our goal is to promote positive attitudes and discussions about skepticism, critical thinking, science, and secularism.
Portland Skeptics in the Pub is a casual social event for people who share an interest in science, skepticism, reason and critical thinking.
We are a group for Worcester-Area Atheists to meet and socialize with like-minded people. We can talk politics, religion, and philosophy if you like.

The Prescott Freethinkers is community-oriented group of skeptics and nontheists that meets for social events, discussion and family-friendly activities. Any science-minded, reason-based thinkers are welcome to join us for fellowship and fun!
Founded in 2011, the Princeton University Society of Humanists is dedicated to promoting and defending rational thought and secular humanism at Princeton and beyond.

Our organization is a community of nonbelievers dedicated to protecting first amendment rights and defending skeptics from intolerance. Our mission is to provide a comfortable and supportive social and theological atmosphere for those of atheistic and agnostic ideologies, support the atheistic and agnostic voice on campus, and create a greater awareness of atheistic and agnostic views.

Pueblo Humanist Directions is a chapter of the American Humanist Association, and we support these goals: To be a clear, democratic voice for Humanism, to increase public awareness, to establish, protect and promote the position of Humanists in our society, to develop and advance Humanist thought and action. So, if you would like to be a PHD, sign up and check us out!

In recent years QSI has become an informal discussion group covering a diverse range of topics. This year the club will continue to meet (weekly or bi-weekly) to discuss an article sent out to members via our mailing list the week before. This year QSI is also going back to its roots in an effort to raise awareness of secular issues and foster a safe, positive space for secular (and inquiring) members of the Queen’s and Kingston communities through events and campaigns.
The Quinte Humanists are a group of individuals with a common interest in secular Humanism who meet regularly for social interaction and learning.
R.E.A.S.O.N - Rationalists, Empiricists And Skeptics Of Nebraska

The mission of R.E.A.S.O.N. (Rationalists, Empiricists and Skeptics of Nebraska) is to encourage critical thinking. Members are dedicated to researching and exposing fallacies in such areas as medical quackery, pseudoscience, Biblical literalism, religious and political extremism, racism, and homophobia. We promote the use of scientific methods, evidence, logic, and reason to gain insight and understanding.
An affiliate of the Secular Student Alliance un Raleigh, NC.

The Rationalist Society Of Saint Louis is the oldest freethought organization in the United States. We are a community of believers -- we believe in insightful trust, but not faith. We believe in the incredible power of good critical thinking skills and are working to develop our ourselves in that way so as to become beacons of rationality in our wider community. We enjoy vigorous debate and educating each other on a broad variety of topics. We meet just about every week to present information and socialize. It is always a small enough gathering that everybody gets ample opportunity to be heard. This group changes lives.

This group is designed for independent thinkers with a focus on reading books that challenge the standard narrative of culture, i.e. concepts that are generally accepted as true by the greater populous, but may not be entirely accurate. We focus on non-fiction, scholarly books that take a critical approach to cultural and technological issues. Every third book, we will switch to fiction that stimulates thinking outside the box.

Reason4Reason is a group of rational thinking activists in the San Francisco Bay Area working to grow the modern skeptical movement and hamper northern California pseudoscience from exporting irrational thinking around the world.

Reasonable Women hopes to provide an opportunity for the secular women of Saskatoon to gather together to talk about what it is like to be an godless woman in our world today, in addition to being a female voice in the "new atheist" movement.
Recovering From Religion Columbus Chapter is a support group encouraging and supporting your journey as you consider the possibility of a life free from faith.
Recovering from Religion - Kansas City, KS
Meet other people who are actively working to eliminate the effects of religion in their lives.
Recovering from Religion - Lees Summit, MO

We are recovering from every imagineable religion: Baptists, Mormons, Catholics, Jehovah\'s Witnesses, Hindus, Muslims, Lutherans, Pentecostals, Evangelicals, and many more. We are happy, we are healthy, and we warmly welcome you to a life free of the confines of faith.

Recovering From Religion is a support group for people letting go of religion. If you are one of the many people who have determined that religion no longer has a place in their life, but are still dealing with the after-effects in some way or another, Recovering From Religion (RR) may be just the right spot for you.
Recovering From Religion - Portland Oregon Chapter
Thousands of organizations will help you get INTO religion, but we are the only one helping you OUT.
Recovering From Religion If you are one of the millions of people who have determined that religion no longer has a place in your life, this may be the right Meetup Group for you.
Leaving a faith community behind can be a tough journey. You are not alone. This is a place to discuss that journey and hear about the experiences of others.
Recovering From Religion is a support group encouraging and supporting your journey as you consider the possibility of a life free from faith.

Red Bank Humanists, formed in October 2003, offers a variety of activities for the Humanist community in Monmouth County. Atheist? Agnostic? Freethinker? Secularist? Post-theological? Forums offer presentations on provocative topics related to Humanism, followed by an open, moderated, lively yet civil discussion.
The Red River Freethinkers group regularly holds four events each month.

Penn Secular Society aims to foster community among the irreligious, provide a haven wherein members may discuss religion and related issues, and encourage the Penn community to think critically about their beliefs.

Reno Freethinkers is a secular organization which meets twice a month (sometimes more!) for group discussion, community, volunteering, and the occasional social event. Reno Freethinkers focuses discussion around humanist, atheist, agnostic, freethought, skeptic, science, philosophy, and other non-theistic topics. All are welcome, regardless of personal beliefs, and we expect our members to come with a respectful, open and critical mind.

\"Promoting Science Education, Rational Thought and Skeptical Inquiry in northern Nevada and the Lake Tahoe Area\"
Reno Skeptical Society, Inc. (aka Reno Skeptics) is a Nevada Non-Profit Corporation and Federal 501(c)(3) Non-Profit Organization.
The mission of Reno Skeptics is to educate those in Northern Nevada and the Lake Tahoe Area to the application and benefits of the scientific method and critical thought; and to the growing local promotion of pseudoscience, paranormal, supernatural and other irrational beliefs.

Had enough of politics as usual, religious fanatics, superstitions and the lack of logic in todays society? Yearning to talk with someone rational for awhile? Meetup with other local skeptics for some refreshing and sane conversation.

Calling all Atheists, Agnostics, FreeThinkers, Humanists, Secularists, Brights, Skeptics, Philosophers, and those who are questioning religion. Gotham Atheists is about secular, science, and social human interactions. Being secular in your approach to life, science minded in your decision making and know we are social humans for a kind, easy going, and helpful group that you want to belong to.
Richmond Reason and Naturalism Association Meetup (RRNA)
Richmond Reason and Naturalism Association Meetup (RRNA)

The Riverdale-Yonkers Society for Ethical Culture, founded in 1948, engages in projects and activities which benefit our neighbors in need as well as aids communities around the world. Here, as in most Ethical Societies, members and friends gather at the Sunday Platform to hear talks on issues ranging from global warming to community gardens and to participate in events and festivals. Our Society strives to be a warm and welcoming place where all are welcome and all are encouraged to become actively involved in the life of the community.
Meet with others to discuss and socialize. Atheists, Agnostics, Humanists, and all others welcome.
Roswatheists is a group of people who are atheist or agnostic.

Uniting all Sacramento City College freethinkers (atheists, agnostics, secularists, humanists, and other skeptics) and providing an opportunity to socialize with like-minded individuals, question religious and theistic beliefs, and promote free thought through campus and community events.

The Sacramento Area Skeptics were created in August 2008 in an effort to promote science, critical thinking, and skepticism in the Sacramento Area as well as organize a way for skeptics in the greater Sacramento area to meet one another. The SAS initially started on meetup.com and has grown since then. In addition to promoting science and skepticism on our websites, we organize lectures, and host a Drinking Skeptically event in Sacramento on the third Friday of every month.

A bright is a person who has a naturalistic worldview free of supernatural and mystical elements. The ethics and actions of a bright are based on a naturalistic worldview. If your worldview is naturalistic, you are by definition a bright! Meet other brights, have some fun, and at the same time achieve something worthwhile! Besides enjoying the camaraderie, we will gather to put some of our ideas into motion - try to make some changes in our locale (e.g., in schools, libraries, and other civic institutions).
Sacramento Freethinkers, Atheists, and Nonbelievers (Sac FAN)

Meet other freethinkers, atheists and nonbelievers in the greater Sacramento area. We strive to build a fun and meaningful community with one another through: monthly meetings, potlucks, guest speakers, book discussions, film screenings, community outreach and other social activities.

The Secular Student Alliance (SSA) of Sacramento State University is a student-run group made up of atheists, agnostics, skeptics, and other Freethinkers organized to provide community, dialogue and events to secular students.

We are a group of SaddleBrooke residents, who, according to our organizational charter "believe in the responsible search for truth and meaning and in the application of reason and science to the understanding of the universe and the solving of human problems. We believe that tolerance, compassion, equity and civility should characterize the interaction among peace-loving persons and organizations."

A Most Worthy, Socially Friendly Group With An Advanced Level of Consciousness, Promoting Happiness and Peace of Mind - Offering a god Free Zone, Good food, Safe close parking and plenty of +Vibes+ for getting acquainted.
PostMos - Salt Lake City Postmormons AND Friends
Our mission is to provide and maintain systems that facilitate the growth and development of a safe and supportive community for those who leave or are considering leaving the Mormon Church.
San Antonio Intellectuals, Eclectics, Bohemians and Nerds

Our Meetup Group is designed for people interested in a wide range of activities. We\'re open to suggestions from members (Eclectics), but as a rule we plan things to stimulate the mind and the senses. For instance, we might meet at a coffee house to discuss provocative issues like Sex Education in Public Schools or the Ramifications of Illegal Immigration. We might have an evening of board games at a small cafe, or go listen to a jazz jam session. We may even meet to discuss topics having to do with science. So, submit your ideas so we can do the things our members want to do!

SASS brings together students from San Antonio area who have a secular outlook. The goal is to foster community communication, education, and activities among secular students. Students from high school to college all the way through PhD are welcome to join.
This group is dedicated to the promotion of critical thinking, science, consumer protection against pseudoscientific claims, and anything else that falls under the "skeptical" umbrella.
San Diego North County Atheists and Agnostics

We welcome atheists, agnostics, secularists, and humanists in the North County San Diego area, and proximal regions. The objective of this group is to bring like-minded individuals together for fun, recreation, and intellectual activities. We offer the benefits of human social interaction, without the interference of religion or superstitious dogma.
San Diego Association for Rational Inquiry (SDARI)

Almost daily we are confronted with tales of paranormal occurrences, or of claims that stem cell research is the deliberate slaughter of innocent (if incipient) babies. Evolution is considered "just a theory" and something called intelligent design offered as a more plausible explanation of who we are and how we got here. The list is endless. In 1995 the San Diego Association for Rational Inquiry (SDARI) was established to challenge such credulous thinking and to offer science as a better way of deciding questions.
San Diego Military Association of Atheists & Freethinkers

The primary goal of San Diego MAAF is building a community for atheists, humanists and freethinkers serving in the San Diego area. By establishing this group, we aim to support each member whether at home or deployed around the world. All Active Duty military and Veterans of all armed services are welcome to join.

San Diego skeptics are a bunch of bad ass critical thinkers. We believe that learning how to think is more important than learning what to think. We are tired of the age old questions about god and religion. Those questions have no relevance in the day to day life of someone who believes that science is the best method that human beings have found for finding truth. Why hang out with the San Diego Skeptics? Because it is self-defense for the mind.

San Francisco Atheists is one of the most active atheist-related organizations in the Bay Area. We provide friendship, education, and activism for hundreds of local atheists. We are officially affiliated with American Atheists, and closely connected to other groups in the Bay Area. While many of our members simply seek the fellowship of other atheists, some of our members are leading activists.
Santa Cruz Skeptics Without A Cause (SWAC)

SWAC is a group that hosts informal social events designed to promote fellowship and social networking among skeptics, critical thinkers, and other like-minded individuals. Like Skeptics in the Pub, we want to provide opportunities for skeptics and rationalists to talk and share ideas in a casual, relaxed atmosphere. And have fun while promoting skepticism, science, and rationality.

The Santa Fe Chapter of Recovering from Religion is part of a nationwide network of peer-to-peer support groups for the ex-religious. It can be difficult to leave religious community in various ways. Recovering from Religion is a safe place to talk about those difficulties with like-minded people
Atheists, secular humanists, agnostics, non-religious people in Sarasota and Manatee Counties who care about Church-State separation and supporting the growth of the secular and humanist movements.

The purpose of this group is to explore ways to raise our children outside the influence of religious institutions. The focus of our group is not to be anti-religious in our activities, but moreso to encourage critical thinking skills in our kids, along with fostering an appreciation of the natural world around them.

SBU Freethinkers represent the secular student body of Stony Brook University. The group aims to foster constructive discussion between students, faculty, and guests based around social and moral issues that impact our society. SBU Freethinkers seek to portray a positive image of active and concerned atheists. The organization is breaking through the common comparison of organizing atheists to herding cats by bringing people together around a cause greater than organization for the sake of authority and dogma. Freethinkers come together to inspire one another and appreciate our freedom of thought and speech.

SCAD Freethinkers: League of Atheists, Agnostics, and Skeptics is organized to promote and defend reason, science, secularism, and freedom of inquiry through education while both trying to improve the image of atheists and providing an intellectual and social outlet for such individuals.
This atheist group is the first to meet on a public beach, where we can blend of social mixing and discussions, although we meet at local restaurants during the colder months.
A peaceful group of freethinking individuals that enjoy getting together for a god-free, good time in Searcy, Arkansas.

SA is a non-profit organization dedicated to serving the atheist community in the Seattle area. We strive to promote understanding & respect toward all freethinkers by providing information, creating a sense of fellowship, actively opposing discrimination, and emphasizing reason & critical thinking over supernaturalism.
Secular Alliance at the University of Chicago
The Secular Alliance at the University of Chicago.
Secular Alliance of IU (SAIU), University of Indiana, Bloomington
Secular Alliance of IU (SAIU), University of Indiana, Bloomington
We are a Secular Association of Skeptical Students group at Colgate University. Our goal is to promote education, cooperation, and action within a community for students who hold secular beliefs.

This is a group for anyone interested in arts, business, lectures, music, science, technology, outdoors, family events, education, book clubs and any event that can be organized with a secular approach.

This group is an opportunity in Fort Collins for non-religious families (of all types!) to form a supportive community around secular parenting. We welcome atheists, agnostics, skeptics, humanists, Unitarians, freethinkers, etc. Our activities include playgroups, crafts centered around different cultures and traditions, moms and dads nights out, family potlucks, volunteerism, local events and more!

This group is for secular families in Northwest Arkansas. We are a local secular group, consisting of families who seek to establish a community free from religious agendas. This may include families who are agnostic, atheist, humanist, freethinker-based, or one who just seeks to provide a religious free environment for their children despite their personal belief systems.

Summit County Secular Freethinkers (formerly: Humanists and Freethinkers) is a member of the Colorado Coalition of Reason and wishes to bring people together to promote the understanding and acceptance of free-thought and rationality with public education, good deeds, group activities and affiliations with other secular groups.

Purpose of this organization: I - To provide a forum for rational discussion of non-religious based philosophies, the role of religion in the public sphere, and related issues of secularism, including separation of church and state. This will be done by sponsoring lectures, films, discussions, and social events.
II - To create a community in which non-religious people, such as freethinkers, skeptics, atheists, agnostics, humanists, and those with naturalistic world views feel welcome and comfortable.
III - To defend freedom of expression and civil liberties for all, religious and non-religious persons alike.
IV - To promote ethical actions that stem from the notion that people must take responsibility for their own lives and the communities and world in which we live.

As a group of students of the University of Utah, located in Salt Lake City, Utah, SHIFT affirms that it IS possible to be good without belief in a god! We form a student body of free-thinking individuals who encourage academic honesty, personal integrity, compassionate service, and coexistence with all human beings.
Secular Humanist Families of North County

Secular Humanist Families of North County We are liberal secular humanists who would like to find a community of like-minded families interested in building strong friendships. We invite you to join us regardless of the label you choose - Agnostic, Bright, Atheist - or no label at all. We simply want to build a community based on principles free from religion and supernaturalism.
Secular Humanist Friendship Group of Merrimack Valley, Londonderry
Celebrating Reason and Humanity. A member of the Alliance of Secular Humanist Societies.
Secular Humanist Society of New York
SHSNY is an Affiliated Local Group of the Council for Secular Humanism, and a Charter Chapter of the American Humanist Association.
Secular Humanists of East Portland (SHEP) Meetup
A bimonthly gathering of secular humanists on the East side of town. Activities usually consist of watching evidenced based documentaries, potlucks, and game nights.
The Roanoke Area Non-Theists meet in the Roanoke area for social, activist, educational, and philanthropic events.
Secular Humanists of the Greater Quad Cities Area (Quad City area)

Our meetup was created to support and promote humanism in the Greater Quad Cities. Our group is for humanists, atheists, freethinkers, skeptics and others with a naturalistic worldview to find support for their commitment to reason in a culture too often inundated by religion and irrational thought. We meet for fun, friendship, discussions, films and more.
Secular Humanists of the Low Country (Lowcountry)

The Secular Humanists of the Lowcountry was founded in 1994 by a group of local non-theists in Charleston, South Carolina. Our members are freethinkers of many kinds. We call ourselves agnostics, atheists, skeptics, secular humanists, rationalists and scientific naturalists. We welcome you and all who are interested in participating in our friendly community, either as members or observers. The purpose of our non-profit, educational organization is to promote the non-theistic, human-centered viewpoint as a valid contribution to public discourse and to strive to maintain the First Amendment guarantee of separation of state and church.
Secular Humanists of the South Carolina Midlands
Secular Humanists of the South Carolina Midlands
The aim of this group is to raise awareness and stir action among the humanists, atheists, agnostics, freethinkers, and other like-minded citizens in Westchester, Rockland, and Putnam Counties.
Secular Jewish Circle of Puget Sound, WA

The mission of SJC is to bring people together to celebrate Jewish culture and heritage in a non-religious setting. We are committed to building our community and improving our world through cultural and educational activities and social activism.

The purposes of the Secular Legal Society are to provide community to atheists, agnostics, humanists, freethinkers, and other nontheists, educate ourselves and the law school community about science, nontheism, and church/state separation, and advocate for church/state separation and the rights of nontheists.

This is a meetup for parents who are raising their children without religion, who love reason as well as art, and who are looking for a community where they can find fun, support, and great company for themselves and their children. Together, we join forces to develop and support secular humanistic values in our families. We get the benefits of church without the dogma.

This is a social group geared towards secular families. Freethinkers, atheists, agnostics, skeptics, humanists etc. are welcome. We get together for activities for families with children. Some events are for younger children and some for older.

We hold weekly services that celebrate the upward spiral of life, and weekly work bees that allow us to contribute to life in creative ways that would be unavailable to us if we did not deliberately step outside the rat race. Our most significant events occur around the changes in the season, and often include a several-day reflective retreat held at a beautiful location in the Pacific Northwest.

Freethinkers are those that have the courage to question commonly held beliefs. Whether you call yourself a believer, non-believer, atheist, agnostic, philosopher, scientist, artist, seeker, or scholar you are welcome to join us.
This group is open to all agnostics, atheists, brights, humanists, skeptics, rationalists, and science enthusiasts!

We discuss the issues of the day and whatever else is on our minds. But most of all, we have fun while promoting skepticism, science, reason and rationality.

SEAFA\'s purpose is to provide educational opportunities to residents of southeast Alabama, primarily regarding the Constitutional principle of Church/State Separation and the theory of evolution through natural selection. SEAFA will work to combat discrimination against atheists, agnostics, humanists and other freethinkers and in the process provide opportunities for socializing, networking, and friendship.

The Springfield Freethinkers serves as a community for non-believers and skeptics. Very much a big tent group, we strive to be warm and welcoming, and to give people a place to make new friends. Camp Quest was founded in 1996 by a small group of dedicated and energetic people with the Free Inquiry Group of Cincinnati and Northern Kentucky.
The idea to offer a summer camp program designed for children from atheist, agnostic, humanist, and other freethinking families originated partially in response to the Boy Scouts of America’s increasing enforcement of their policy requiring boys to profess a belief in God. It became clear that children from nontheistic families needed their own place to belong and enjoy the summer camp experience.
The first Camp Quest session, serving 20 campers ages 8-12, was held in Boone County, Kentucky in August of 1996.
As Camp Quest grew, it expanded to serve teenagers ages 13-17 as well as children 8-12. Campers traveled from across the U.S., as well as from Canada, the UK, Japan, and the Curacao Islands to attend Camp Quest sessions.
And today…
Camp Quest NorthWest’s inaugural session was held August 15-21, 2012 at beautiful Camp Kirby in Samish, WA. We look forward to welcoming campers from ages 8-15 years, with campers ages 16-17 years acting as Counselors in Training.

Members of our community and student organizations self identify as atheist, agnostic, humanist, freethinker, secular, skeptic, non-religious, rationalist, empiricist, and more. Mid-Ohio Valley Atheists and Humanists (hereinafter referred to as MOVAH) exists to promote secular thought, provide a safe atmosphere for the congregation of free-thinkers and extend the values of humanism in our region. To further that goal it engages in activities including but not limited to discussions of secular and religious ideas in politics, philosophy, morality, science, and the social sciences; events airing secular and skeptical views or reaching out to the general public; the gathering together of individuals with a common goal and intent to lead ethical lives of personal fulfillment that aspire to the greater good of humanity.
The group does not discriminate on the basis of personal characteristics including but not limited to religion, gender, gender identity, race, sexual orientation, nationality, age, political beliefs,disability, socioeconomic or marital status. To that end we also welcome those who may not self-identify as either “atheist” or “humanist,” but seek to associate with us due to our values and mission.
